  "title": "Day 2 (29 January 2026)",
  "body": " Day 2 (29 January 2026)   This is an outline of the plans for Day 2 of the class.      Thursday 1\/29  Today's agenda:  Welcome  Roll: pronunciation  Collect Homework  Questions  New material      Topic Outline  In mathematics, rigor refers to solid mathematical proof.  Reading, creating, and writing proofs will be a central part of this course.  Here are the general topics we will learn about in this coruse:  The real numbers and other number systems (e.g., the rationals, irrationals)  How the real numbers are complete and form a continuum  Sequences and series of real numbers and their convergense  The topology of the reals, and topological concepts that help us understand functions  Functions, their limits, and their properties  Sequences of functions and their convergence  Function spaces, their properties and uses    We will practice proof techniques we've learned before, and we will learn new techniques.  What are some proof techniques that you've studied before?    Number systems: the numbers  The set of natural numbers (denoted by ) forms the most elementary and familiar system of numbers in mathematics.  The set of integers (denoted by , from the German word for number, Zahlen ) augments the naturals with zero and negative counting numbers.  The set of rational numbers (denoted by , for quotient) adds lots of fractional numbers.  The Greeks get credit for being the first society that investigated mathematics rigorously. They believed \"all is number\" and by \"number\" they mean rational numbers.    Number systems:the operations  What are the basic operations endowed to , , and ?  The sets are also ordered. What does this mean?  Without getting too deep into the concept of algebraic structure of these systems, all these systems are called ordered commutative rings because  they have (and are closed under) two operations: addition and multiplication  both two operations are commutative and associative  multiplication is distributive over addition  addition has an inverse  and both operations have an identity   The rationals is also an ordered commutative ring, but it has a bit more 'structure' because everyt element has a multiplicative inverse. This means that the rational numbers form a field .  The Greeks believed every number was rational.  They were wrong.    Irrational numbers  What is an irrational number?  Give a few examples of irrational numbers?  Are the irrational numbers a field?    Irrational numbers    The number is an irrational number.    We prove this by contradiction or indirectly. Suppose is not irrational. This means that the number is rational. This means that can be expressed as where and are natural numbers.  Without loss of generality, we can assume is a proper fraction (the numerator and denominator have no prime factors in common).  Then so .  The left-hand side of this equation is an even number, so is even, too. This means 2 is a prime factor of . But all prime factrors of appear at least twice, so we know is event. This means for some natural number .  This allows us to write . Diving both sides by 2 gives . This shows that must be even, too.  We already showed that was even, and we began this proof by assuming that and had no common prime factors. So cannot be even. This is our contradiction.  Consequently, we deduce that cannot be rational. It must be irrational, as originally claimed.      Constructing the Real Number system  Mathematician knew they needed a number system that formed a continuum ( i.e. , has no holes) and shares the algebraic properties of the rational number field.  To this point in our mathematical education, we've worked with the real numbers withot knowing much about what they are and where they came from.  In this course, we will construct them, starting from the rational numbers, as the Greeks would have wanted.    Sets and Operations  (I expect the following to be review from Transitions and Discrete .)  A set is a collection of elements .  Let be a set.  If is an element of , we write  If is not an element of , we write  There are two main kinds of set notation: roster notation and set-builder notation.  A set is represented in roster notation if its elements are written out, separated by commas, and this list is wrapped in curley braces, { and } . When we represent a set in set-builder notation we use curley braces as before, but the elements of the set are described differently; the notation looks like or where 'element' is a symbolic representation of the set elements, and 'rule' is some pattern that the elements follow. This is best described with some examples.   A Set and Elements  If then and .    Set of all even numbers  The set of all even numbers in roster notation would be . In set-builder notation we could write this as .    An infinite solution set  The set of solutions to is . In roster notation this might look like     The set of real numbers strictly between is called an open interval from to and is denoted by . Note that .  The set of real numbers between inclusive is called a closed interval from to and is denoted by . Note that .     There are three important operations on sets: union, intersection, and complement.  Set Union  If and are sets, the union of and is denoted by and is the set consisting of elements that are either in set or in set .   If and if , then .   Set Intersection  If and are sets, the intersection of and is denoted by and is the set consisting of elements that are in both set and in set .   If and if , then .   Subset  The set is a subset of another set if every element in is also in . If is a subset of we write .    If is the set of even numbers, then .     Set Complement  The complement of a set is relative to another set that contains , i.e. , .  If , then the complement of , denoted by , i the set of elements in that are not in .    In , the complement of the positive numbers is the non-positive numbers, .    In , the complement of the odd numbers is the even numbers.    In , the complement of is the irrational numbers.     If we have multiple sets, , , , , we can take the union of all the sets or the intersection of all the sets. Special notation for these are (respectively) .  Union, intersection, and complement come together in DeMorgan's Law.  DeMorgan's Law  If , , , are sets, then . In fact, the equality holds for infinite collections of sets, too.   You should be able to prove this theorem.    Bounded Sets    A set is bounded above if there is an for which for all .  A set is bounded below if there is an for which for all .  A set is totally bounded if there is an for which for all .      Each of the following sets in bounded in one way or another. For each, find an upper bound and a lower bound and a total bound, if possible.            "
