  "title": "Day 5 (10 February 2026)",
  "body": " Day 5 (10 February 2026)   This is an outline of the plans for Day 4 of the class.      Tuesday 2\/10  Today's agenda:  Roll  Homework due Thursday  NOTE: the Teamsters are striking next week, starting on 17 Feb. This may disrupt campus. If you want to support those who are striking, talk with Miller if you want to know what to expect when the strike happens.  Questions on anything?  New material      Consequences of Completeness   Density of in  Let with . Then there is an with .    Let and be real numbers with . We need to find integers and where .  First, we look for the . It's the denominator of our rational number, so the closer and are to one another, the larger will be. Consider the real number .  By the Archimedean Property of real numbers, there is an with . Now let's start looking for .  We want . This is equivalent to wanting . We choose the smallest integer for which . (This is rounded up to the nearest integer.). It follows that .  Now we want to relate our rational number to . Since and , we can write . Consequently, .  We conclude that , as desired.     How big is that set?  To get a better understanding of the reals, we're going to develop the concept of set cardinality , which is essenially a measurement of the size of a set.    A set is finite if there is an for which the elements of the set and the elements of the set can be put in 1-1 correspondence.    We say that this correspondence is an enumeration of the set .  >What does it mean to \"put in 1-1 correspondence\" the elements of two sets?   Enumerations   Function   A function from a set to a set is a rule that assigns to each input exactly one output .    What mathematics vocabulary and concepts do you associate with the concept of function?   Enumerations   Function   A function from a set to a set is a rule that assigns to each input exactly one output .     one-to-one function   A function  is one-to-one if means that .    What are some examples of one-to-one functions?   A function that is one-to-one has an inverse . Inverse functions are characterized by for all , and for all .     onto function   A function  is onto if for every there is an with .    What are some examples of onto functions?   Enumerations   bijection   A function  is a bijection if it is both one-to-one and onto.    The cardinality of a set is the number of elements in .  If a set is finite, the cardinality is the number of elements in the set. If a set is not finite, we say it is an infinite set.    Two sets and have the same cardinality if there is a bijection .     Even and Odd numbers  Let be the set of even numbers. Let be the set of odd numbers.  Show that and have the same cardinality.  Show that and have the same cardinality.  Do and have the same cardinality.?  > If ( is a proper subset of ), it is possible that and could have the same cardinality.  We saw this with the even numbers, odd numbers, and .   Infinite Sets   Naturals and Integers  The natural numbers and the integers have the same cardinality.   >  Countability   A set is countable (or countably infinite ) if it has the same cardinality as .     Uncountable   A set is uncountable (or uncountably infinite ) if it is infinite but not countable.     Infinite Sets    The set of rational numbers is countable.    Let be all the negative rationals and let be all the positive rationals. We will show that is countable.  Once we see that is countable, we will have an enumeration of its elements . It follows that is countable and has some enumeration . This allows us to arrange the elements of into an array with two rows:      We can enumerate this array by snaking through the array in a way that defines a bijection from to the array.  This demonstrates that is countable, as claimed.  To see that is countable, arrange the rational numbers in a doubly-infinite array as follows:       . All rational numbers show up multiple times in this array. For each rational number in the array, we throw away all copies of the rational number except the copy that is in lowest terms. When we throw away a rational number, we shift all the entries in its row to the left to fill the gap it leaves (and the gaps they create when they shift).  This leaves us an array of rational numbers in lowest terms.  By snaking through the array starting in the upper left corner and moving anti-diagonally (transverse to the array's diagonal entries), we create an enumeration from to . This shows that is countable.  This concludes the proof that is countable.   >  Infinite Sets    The set of real numbers is uncountable.    (Contradiction). Suppose is countable. Then there exists an enumeratioon . Let so that . We are going to construct a nested sequence of closed and bounded intervals that and use the Nested Interval Principle to generate a contradiction.  Let be a closed and bounded interval that does not contain .  Let be a closed and bounded interval that does not contain . Why can we do this? If , then we can take . If , then divides into two complementary closed intervals and with and . Take so that .  Continue in this way to define closed and bounded intervals with and .  Consider . The Nested Interval Property tells us that is nonempty. Let . The Nested Interval Property tells us that is a real number.  Since is countable, this is in our enumeration, so for some . But , so . This is a contradiction.  Therefore, our supposition that is countably infinte was false. The opposite is true: is uncountable.   >   The set of irrational numbers is uncountable.   >    "
