  "body": "  The set of rational numbers is countable.    Let be all the negative rationals and let be all the positive rationals. We will show that is countable.  Once we see that is countable, we will have an enumeration of its elements . It follows that is countable and has some enumeration . This allows us to arrange the elements of into an array with two rows:      We can enumerate this array by snaking through the array in a way that defines a bijection from to the array.  This demonstrates that is countable, as claimed.  To see that is countable, arrange the rational numbers in a doubly-infinite array as follows:       . All rational numbers show up multiple times in this array. For each rational number in the array, we throw away all copies of the rational number except the copy that is in lowest terms. When we throw away a rational number, we shift all the entries in its row to the left to fill the gap it leaves (and the gaps they create when they shift).  This leaves us an array of rational numbers in lowest terms.  By snaking through the array starting in the upper left corner and moving anti-diagonally (transverse to the array's diagonal entries), we create an enumeration from to . This shows that is countable.  This concludes the proof that is countable.   "
