  "body": " Day 10 (26 February 2026)   This is an outline of the plans for Day 10 of the class.      Thursday 2\/26  Today's agenda:  Roll  Next Homework due Tuesday:  2.3:  1, 2, 7, 8, 10, 12  2.4: 1, 3, 8  Also, work the following problems: For a sequence we write provided for each there is a number of such that implies that .  In this case, we say diverges to .  Similarly, we write provided for each there is a number of such that implies that .  In this case, we say diverges to .   A.  Suppose that diverges to .  Suppose there is an for which if then .  Prove the following.  A1. If then .  A2. If then .  A3. If and exist, then .  B.  Let and be sequences where and .  Prove that .    Questions on anything?  New material      Algebraic Limit Theorem  Last time: Algebraic Limit Theorems and their proofs.   If and are a convergent sequences with and , then  for all  ,  , and  so long as .        Proof of \" so long as \"     Order Limit Theorems   Assume and .  If for all then .  If for all then .  If there exists a for which for all then . Likewise, if for all then .      Proof of ``If for all then .''      Proof of ``If for all then .''  By the algebraic limit theorem, the sequence converges to . By the first part of the Order Limit Theorem, since or all , we know . Therefore, , as desired.    Proof of ``If there exists a for which for all then . Likewise, if for all then .''  Take , the constant sequence and the result follows by the second part of the Order Limit Theorem. Likewise, take and the second part of the statement follows from the second part of the Order Limit Theorem.     Monotone Sequences    A sequence is increasing if for all and decreasing if for all . A sequence is monotone if it is either increasing or decreasing.     Monotone Convergence Theorem  If a sequence is monotone and bounded, then it converges.   Assume the sequence is bounded and monotone. Since it is bounded, it is both bounded above and bonded below.  Consider the case where is increasing. Then the set is bonded above. By the Axiom of Completeness, has a least upper bound . We claim that .  Let be given. By Lemma 1.3.8, is not an upper bound for . So there exists a point in the sequence at which . Since our sequence is increasing, we know that if then . Therefore, .  This means that . Therefore, , as desired.  The case where is decreasing is proved using the analogous results for the infimum of a bounded set of real numbers.      Subsequences    Let be a sequence of real numbers, and let be an increasing sequence of natural numbers. Then the sequence is called a subsequence of and is denoted by , where indexews the subsequence.     Subsequences of a convergent sequence converge to the same limit as the original sequence.      "
