  "body": " Day 15 (23 March 2026)   This is an outline of the plans for Day 15 of the class.      Tuesday 3\/23  Today's agenda:  Roll  Next Homework due ... : see Canvas  Midterm: Thursday 2 April  review session?  New material      Before break ...  Open set of reals.   Open Set   A set is called an open set if for every there is an for which .    Closed sets of reals, limit point of a set, and isolated point of a set.   Closed Set   A set is called a closed set if it contains all its limit points.    Canonical example, a closed and bounded interval: .  Other examples of close sets: the real line , the empty set, a finite set of points.     Closure    Let . If is the set of limit points of , then the closure of is .      If , then is a closed set.    If this theorem is true, we will day that the set is the ``smallest closed set that contains .''   Let denote the limit points of . Then .  We must show that contains all its limit points. Let be a limit point of . We must show .  Since is a limit point of , there is a sequence that converges to . We will show that .  We will do so by showing there is exists a sequence (to be named later) in that converges to .  One of two things can be true of the sequence : it is either eventually in , or it is not eventually in . The former means that there is an for which is then . The latter means that for any we can find a for which .  Consider the case where is eventually in . This means the entire tail of is in , so that tail is a sequence in that converges to . Thus by Theorem 3.2.5. of the textbook.  Now, consider the alternative case. If is not eventually in , then there is a subsequence of for which .      Define a new sequence by taking . Since each is a limit point of , we can construct a sequence that converges to , for each , in the following way. For , we know that each contains a point of that is different from . Call this point . For each , this defines a sequence that converges to as grows without bound.  Let . This defines a sequence . We claim that . Consequently, by textbook theorem 3.2.5.  To see that , let be given. Because converges to , and because is a subsequence of , it must also converge to . Therefore, there is an for which if then . By construction, there is an for which for all . Let , and let . Then . This shows that is a limit point of , as desired.     Complements  Open sets and closed sets have this important relationships.   A set is open if and only if is closed. Similarly, a set is closed if and only if is open.    Suppose is open. We musth show is closed. That means we must show that contains all its limit points. Let be a limit point of . Then for every , the set contains a point of that is different from . Were , then there would be an for which this was impossible! Therefore, .  Suppose is closed. We will show must be open. Let . We must find an for which . Because is closed, is not a limit point of ; it is isolated from , which means there is an for which does not intersect . This means , as desired.  This proves the first statement.  To prove the second statement, note that if is a set, the . So we can prove the second statement using the first and this fact abo complements.     Complements  A closing fact (haha!) about closed sets can be proved using DeMorgan's Laws and Theorem 3.2.3, the analogous result for open sets.     The union of a finite number of closed sets is a closed set.  The intersection of an arbitrary number of closed sets is a closed set.     Note that Theorem 3.2.3 can be summarized by saying that open sets like unions; this theorem can be summarized by saying that closed sets like intersections.  Next, we talk about compact sets.    A set is compact if every sequences in has a subsequence that converges in .         "
